The compiler should give you an error if you forgot to initialise a `static final` field.

As for throwing an exception when it is initialised to null, you can use [`Objects.requireNonNull`][1], which is almost like an &quot;annotation&quot;. You can optionally supply an error message.

    REGION = Objects.requireNonNull(prop.getProperty(&quot;aws.region&quot;));
    APP_PEEFIX = Objects.requireNonNull(
        prop.getProperty(&quot;cdk.appprefix&quot;), &quot;App prefix is null!&quot;
    );

This throws a `NullPointerException` if the value is null, which is a kind of `RuntimeException`.

Alternatively, since you are always using `getProperty` to initialise the properties, you can write a `@NotNull` method that wraps around it:

    private static final Properties prop = new Properties();
    @NotNull
    private static getProperty(String key) {
        return prop.getProperty(key);
    }

You can configure IntelliJ to generate a null check for this:

[![enter image description here][2]][2]

At runtime, an `ExceptionInInitializerError` will be thrown, which is not a `RuntimeException`, but there is an `IllegalStateException` as the cause, with an appropriate message.




  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/util/Objects.html#requireNonNull(T)
  [2]: https://i.stack.imgur.com/PSuN5.png

One option is [decorating][1] `Properties` with a class that throws the exception on calling `getProperty()`

    import java.util.Properties;
    
    public class NonNullProperties extends Properties {
        private final Properties mProps;
    
        public NonNullProperties(Properties props) {
            mProps = props;
        }
    
        @Override
        public String getProperty(String key) {
            String property = super.getProperty(key);
            if (property == null) {
                throw new  NullPointerException(key + &quot; was null!&quot;);
            }
            
            return  property;
        }
    
        // OVERRIDE AND DELEGATE OTHER METHODS
    }

Then the only thing you have to change in your code is wrapping the Properties class.

    Properties prop = new NonNullProperties(new Properties());

  [1]: https://www.google.com/search?q=java%20decorator%20pattern

